I was only 10 in 1968 and so never had to worry about being drafted or dodging it or trying to end it, but not so young to avoid having the War, as I will always know it, impress itself on me forever.  When I first visited the Wall, I felt as if I were visiting a legion of dead brothers, whom I would have believed with the certainty and trust that only a 10 year old could have would have explained Why?<br><br>
  In 1976, I did attempt to register for the draft, because I thought I was legally obligated to do so and was living in England at the time and was frankly tired of listening to Europeans keep telling me what a bunch of monsters we American were for having been in Vietnam, while also being told what a bunch of silly idealists the Protesters on the Home Front were.  After spending an hour at the Embassy in Grosvenor Square and having talked to an junior Consel and the Marine Corps officer, realized that at least part of it was really over.<br><br>
  I can only hope that I would have had half the courage that both those who went and those who stayed at home and fought on whatever front they found themselves had.
